[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] In statistics, an **exchangeable sequence of random variables** (also sometimes **interchangeable**) is a sequence *X*1, *X*2, *X*3, ...
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] (which may be finitely or infinitely long) whose joint probability distribution does not change when the positions in the sequence in which finitely many of them appear are altered.
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] In other words, the joint distribution is invariant to finite permutation.
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] both have the same joint probability distribution.
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] It is closely related to the use of independent and identically distributed random variables in statistical models.
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] Exchangeable sequences of random variables arise in cases of simple random sampling.
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] is the same as the joint probability distribution of the original sequence.
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] A sequence *E*1, *E*2, *E*3, … of events is said to be exchangeable iff the sequence of its indicator functions is exchangeable.
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] The distribution function *F**X*1, …, *X**n*(*x*1, …, *x**n*) of a finite sequence of exchangeable random variables is symmetric in its arguments *x*1, …, *x**n*.
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] Olav Kallenberg provided an appropriate definition of exchangeability for continuous-time stochastic processes.
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] The concept was introduced by William Ernest Johnson in his 1924 book *Logic, Part III: The Logical Foundations of Science*.
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] Exchangeability is equivalent to the concept of statistical control introduced by Walter Shewhart also in 1924.
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] The property of exchangeability is closely related to the use of independent and identically distributed (i.i.d.) random variables in statistical models.
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] A sequence of random variables that are i.i.d., conditional on some underlying distributional form, is exchangeable.
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] This follows directly from the structure of the joint probability distribution generated by the i.i.d. form.
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] Mixtures of exchangeable sequences (in particular, sequences of i.i.d. variables) are exchangeable.
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] The converse can be established for infinite sequences, through an important representation theorem by Bruno de Finetti (later extended by other probability theorists such as Halmos and Savage).
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] The extended versions of the theorem show that in any infinite sequence of exchangeable random variables, the random variables are conditionally i.i.d., given the underlying distributional form.
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] This means that infinite sequences of exchangeable random variables can be regarded equivalently as sequences of conditionally i.i.d. random variables, based on some underlying distributional form.
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] (Note that this equivalence does not quite hold for finite exchangeability.
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] However, for finite vectors of random variables there is a close approximation to the i.i.d. model.) An infinite exchangeable sequence is strictly stationary and so a law of large numbers in the form of Birkhoff–Khinchin theorem applies.
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] This means that the underlying distribution can be given an operational interpretation as the limiting empirical distribution of the sequence of values.
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] The close relationship between exchangeable sequences of random variables and the i.i.d. form means that the latter can be justified on the basis of infinite exchangeability.
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] This notion is central to Bruno de Finetti’s development of predictive inference and to Bayesian statistics.
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] It can also be shown to be a useful foundational assumption in frequentist statistics and to link the two paradigms.
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] (This is the Cesàro limit of the indicator functions.
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] In cases where the Cesàro limit does not exist this function can actually be defined as the Banach limit of the indicator functions, which is an extension of this limit.
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] These equations show the joint distribution or density characterised as a mixture distribution based on the underlying limiting empirical distribution (or a parameter indexing this distribution).
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] Note that not all finite exchangeable sequences are mixtures of i.i.d..
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] To see this, consider sampling without replacement from a finite set until no elements are left.
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] The resulting sequence is exchangeable, but not a mixture of i.i.d..
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] Indeed, conditioned on all other elements in the sequence, the remaining element is known.
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] Exchangeable sequences have some basic covariance and correlation properties which mean that they are generally positively correlated.
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] For infinite sequences of exchangeable random variables, the covariance between the random variables is equal to the variance of the mean of the underlying distribution function.
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] For finite exchangeable sequences the covariance is also a fixed value which does not depend on the particular random variables in the sequence.
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] There is a weaker lower bound than for infinite exchangeability and it is possible for negative correlation to exist.
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] The finite sequence result may be proved as follows.
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] We can then solve the inequality for the covariance yielding the stated lower bound.
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] The non-negativity of the covariance for the infinite sequence can then be obtained as a limiting result from this finite sequence result.
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] Equality of the lower bound for finite sequences is achieved in a simple urn model: An urn contains 1 red marble and *n* − 1 green marbles, and these are sampled without replacement until the urn is empty.
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] Let *X**i* = 1 if the red marble is drawn on the *i*-th trial and 0 otherwise.
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] A finite sequence that achieves the lower covariance bound cannot be extended to a longer exchangeable sequence.
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] The von Neumann extractor is a randomness extractor that depends on exchangeability: it gives a method to take an exchangeable sequence of 0s and 1s (Bernoulli trials), with some probability *p* of 0 and $q=1-p$ of 1, and produce a (shorter) exchangeable sequence of 0s and 1s with probability 1/2.
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] Partition the sequence into non-overlapping pairs: if the two elements of the pair are equal (00 or 11), discard it; if the two elements of the pair are unequal (01 or 10), keep the first.
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] This yields a sequence of Bernoulli trials with $p=1/2,$ as, by exchangeability, the odds of a given pair being 01 or 10 are equal.
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] Exchangeable random variables arise in the study of U statistics, particularly in the Hoeffding decomposition.
[src:permutation-tests/exchangeability] Exchangeability is a key assumption of the distribution-free inference method of conformal prediction.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are mainly used in three distinct problem classes: optimization, numerical integration, and non-uniform random variate generation, available for modeling phenomena with significant input uncertainties, e.g. risk assessments for nuclear power plants.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are often implemented using computer simulations.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] They can provide approximate solutions to problems too complex for mathematical analysis.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] The name comes from the Monte Carlo Casino in Monaco, where the primary developer of the method, mathematician Stanisław Ulam, was inspired by his uncle's gambling habits.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are widely used in various fields of science, engineering, and mathematics, such as physics, chemistry, biology, statistics, artificial intelligence, finance, and cryptography.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] They have also been applied to social sciences, such as sociology, psychology, and political science.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods have been recognized as one of the most important and influential ideas of the 20th century, and they have enabled many scientific and technological breakthroughs.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods also have some limitations and challenges, such as the trade-off between accuracy and computational cost, the curse of dimensionality, the reliability of random number generators, and the verification and validation of the results.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Generate inputs randomly from a probability distribution over the domain.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Perform a deterministic computation of the outputs.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] For example, consider a quadrant (circular sector) inscribed in a unit square.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Uniformly scatter a given number of points over the square.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Count the number of points inside the quadrant, i.e. having a distance from the origin of less than 1.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] The ratio of the inside-count and the total-sample-count is an estimate of the ratio of the two areas, ⁠π/4⁠.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] In this procedure, the domain of inputs is the square that circumscribes the quadrant.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] One can generate random inputs by scattering grains over the square, then performing a computation on each input to test whether it falls within the quadrant.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Aggregating the results yields our final result, the approximation of π.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] The approximation improves as more points are randomly placed in the whole square.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Uses of Monte Carlo methods require large amounts of random numbers, and their use benefitted greatly from pseudorandom number generators, which are far quicker to use than the tables of random numbers that had been previously employed.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are often used in physical and mathematical problems and are most useful when it is difficult or impossible to use other approaches.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are mainly used in three problem classes: optimization, numerical integration, and generating draws from a probability distribution.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Other examples include modeling phenomena with significant uncertainty in inputs such as the calculation of risk in business and, in mathematics, evaluation of multidimensional definite integrals with complicated boundary conditions.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] In application to systems engineering problems (space, oil exploration, aircraft design, etc.), Monte Carlo–based predictions of failure, cost overruns and schedule overruns are routinely better than human intuition or alternative "soft" methods.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] In principle, Monte Carlo methods can be used to solve any problem having a probabilistic interpretation.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] By the law of large numbers, integrals described by the expected value of some random variable can be approximated by taking the empirical mean (a.k.a. the 'sample mean') of independent samples of the variable.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] When the probability distribution of the variable is parameterized, mathematicians often use a Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) sampler.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] The central idea is to design a judicious Markov chain model with a prescribed stationary probability distribution.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] That is, in the limit, the samples being generated by the MCMC method will be samples from the desired (target) distribution.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] By the ergodic theorem, the stationary distribution is approximated by the empirical measures of the random states of the MCMC sampler.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] In other problems, the objective is generating draws from a sequence of probability distributions satisfying a nonlinear evolution equation.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] These flows of probability distributions can always be interpreted as the distributions of the random states of a Markov process whose transition probabilities depend on the distributions of the current random states (see McKean–Vlasov processes, nonlinear filtering equation).
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] In other instances, a flow of probability distributions with an increasing level of sampling complexity arise (path spaces models with an increasing time horizon, Boltzmann–Gibbs measures associated with decreasing temperature parameters, and many others).
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] These models can also be seen as the evolution of the law of the random states of a nonlinear Markov chain.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] A natural way to simulate these sophisticated nonlinear Markov processes is to sample multiple copies of the process, replacing in the evolution equation the unknown distributions of the random states by the sampled empirical measures.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] In contrast with traditional Monte Carlo and MCMC methodologies, these mean-field particle techniques rely on sequential interacting samples.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] The terminology *mean field* reflects the fact that each of the *samples* (a.k.a. particles, individuals, walkers, agents, creatures, or phenotypes) interacts with the empirical measures of the process.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] When the size of the system tends to infinity, these random empirical measures converge to the deterministic distribution of the random states of the nonlinear Markov chain, so that the statistical interaction between particles vanishes.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Suppose one wants to know the expected value $\mu$ of a population (and knows that $\mu$ exists), but does not have a formula available to compute it.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] The simple Monte Carlo method gives an estimate for $\mu$ by running n simulations and averaging the simulations' results.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] It has no restrictions on the probability distribution of the inputs to the simulations, requiring only that the inputs are randomly generated and are independent of each other and that $\mu$ exists.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] A sufficiently large n will produce a value for m that is arbitrarily close to $\mu$ ; more formally, it will be the case that, for any $\epsilon >0$ , $|\mu -m|\leq \epsilon$ .
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Suppose we want to know how many times we should expect to throw three eight-sided dice for the total of the dice throws to be at least T .
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] The dice throws are randomly distributed and independent of each other.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] If n is large enough, m will be within $\epsilon$ of $\mu$ for any $\epsilon >0$ .
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Choose the desired confidence level – the percent chance that, when the Monte Carlo algorithm completes, m is indeed within $\epsilon$ of $\mu$ .
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Let z be the z -score corresponding to that confidence level.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Let $s^{2}$ be the estimated variance, sometimes called the "sample" variance; it is the variance of the results obtained from a relatively small number k of "sample" simulations.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Note that, when the algorithm completes, $m_{k}$ is the mean of the k results.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] If $n\leq k$ , then $m_{k}=m$ ; sufficient sample simulations were done to ensure that $m_{k}$ is within $\epsilon$ of $\mu$ .
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] An alternative formula can be used in the special case where all simulation results are bounded above and below.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Choose a value for $\epsilon$ that is twice the maximum allowed difference between $\mu$ and m .
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Let $0<\delta <100$ be the desired confidence level, expressed as a percentage.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Let every simulation result $r_{1},r_{2},\ldots ,r_{i},\ldots ,r_{n}$ be such that $a\leq r_{i}\leq b$ for finite a and b .
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Despite its conceptual and algorithmic simplicity, the computational cost associated with a Monte Carlo simulation can be staggeringly high.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] In general the method requires many samples to get a good approximation, which may incur an arbitrarily large total runtime if the processing time of a single sample is high.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Although this is a severe limitation in very complex problems, the embarrassingly parallel nature of the algorithm allows this large cost to be reduced (perhaps to a feasible level) through parallel computing strategies in local processors, clusters, cloud computing, GPU, FPGA, etc.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Before the Monte Carlo method was developed, simulations tested a previously understood deterministic problem, and statistical sampling was used to estimate uncertainties in the simulations.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo simulations invert this approach, solving deterministic problems using probabilistic metaheuristics (see simulated annealing).
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] An early variant of the Monte Carlo method was devised to solve the Buffon's needle problem, in which π can be estimated by dropping needles on a floor made of parallel equidistant strips.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] In the 1930s, Enrico Fermi first experimented with the Monte Carlo method while studying neutron diffusion, but he did not publish this work.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] In the late 1940s, Stanisław Ulam invented the modern version of the Markov Chain Monte Carlo method while he was working on nuclear weapons projects at the Los Alamos National Laboratory.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] In 1946, nuclear weapons physicists at Los Alamos were investigating neutron diffusion in the core of a nuclear weapon.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Being secret, the work of von Neumann and Ulam required a code name.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] A colleague of von Neumann and Ulam, Nicholas Metropolis, suggested using the name *Monte Carlo*, which refers to the Monte Carlo Casino in Monaco where Ulam's uncle would borrow money from relatives to gamble.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods were central to the simulations required for further postwar development of nuclear weapons, including the design of the H-bomb, though severely limited by the computational tools at the time.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Von Neumann, Nicholas Metropolis and others programmed the ENIAC computer to perform the first fully automated Monte Carlo calculations, of a fission weapon core, in the spring of 1948.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] In the 1950s Monte Carlo methods were used at Los Alamos for the development of the hydrogen bomb, and became popularized in the fields of physics, physical chemistry, and operations research.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Air Force were two of the major organizations responsible for funding and disseminating information on Monte Carlo methods during this time, and they began to find a wide application in many different fields.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] The theory of more sophisticated mean-field type particle Monte Carlo methods had certainly started by the mid-1960s, with the work of Henry P.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] McKean Jr. on Markov interpretations of a class of nonlinear parabolic partial differential equations arising in fluid mechanics.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] An earlier pioneering article by Theodore E.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Harris and Herman Kahn, published in 1951, used mean-field genetic-type Monte Carlo methods for estimating particle transmission energies.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Mean-field genetic type Monte Carlo methodologies are also used as heuristic natural search algorithms (a.k.a. metaheuristic) in evolutionary computing.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] The origins of these mean-field computational techniques can be traced to 1950 and 1954 with the work of Alan Turing on genetic type mutation-selection learning machines and the articles by Nils Aall Barricelli at the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton, New Jersey.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Quantum Monte Carlo, and more specifically diffusion Monte Carlo methods can also be interpreted as a mean-field particle Monte Carlo approximation of Feynman–Kac path integrals.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] The origins of Quantum Monte Carlo methods are often attributed to Enrico Fermi and Robert Richtmyer who developed in 1948 a mean-field particle interpretation of neutron-chain reactions, but the first heuristic-like and genetic type particle algorithm (a.k.a.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Resampled or Reconfiguration Monte Carlo methods) for estimating ground state energies of quantum systems (in reduced matrix models) is due to Jack H.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] In molecular chemistry, the use of genetic heuristic-like particle methodologies (a.k.a. pruning and enrichment strategies) can be traced back to 1955 with the seminal work of Marshall N.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] The use of sequential Monte Carlo in advanced signal processing and Bayesian inference is more recent.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] It was in 1993, that Gordon et al., published in their seminal work the first application of a Monte Carlo resampling algorithm in Bayesian statistical inference.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] The authors named their algorithm 'the bootstrap filter', and demonstrated that compared to other filtering methods, their bootstrap algorithm does not require any assumption about that state-space or the noise of the system.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Another pioneering article in this field was Genshiro Kitagawa's, on a related "Monte Carlo filter", and the ones by Pierre Del Moral and Himilcon Carvalho, Pierre Del Moral, André Monin and Gérard Salut on particle filters published in the mid-1990s.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Particle filters were also developed in signal processing in 1989–1992 by P.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Salut in the LAAS-CNRS in a series of restricted and classified research reports with STCAN (Service Technique des Constructions et Armes Navales), the IT company DIGILOG, and the LAAS-CNRS (the Laboratory for Analysis and Architecture of Systems) on radar/sonar and GPS signal processing problems.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] These Sequential Monte Carlo methodologies can be interpreted as an acceptance-rejection sampler equipped with an interacting recycling mechanism.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] The mathematical foundations and the first rigorous analysis of these particle algorithms were written by Pierre Del Moral in 1996.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Branching type particle methodologies with varying population sizes were also developed in the end of the 1990s by Dan Crisan, Jessica Gaines and Terry Lyons, and by Dan Crisan, Pierre Del Moral and Terry Lyons.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Further developments in this field were described in 1999 to 2001 by P.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] There is no consensus on how *Monte Carlo* should be defined.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] For example, Ripley defines most probabilistic modeling as *stochastic simulation*, with *Monte Carlo* being reserved for Monte Carlo integration and Monte Carlo statistical tests.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Sawilowsky distinguishes between a simulation, a Monte Carlo method, and a Monte Carlo simulation: a simulation is a fictitious representation of reality, a Monte Carlo method is a technique that can be used to solve a mathematical or statistical problem.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] A Monte Carlo simulation uses repeated sampling to obtain the statistical properties of some phenomena.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Kalos and Whitlock point out that such distinctions are not always easy to maintain.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] For example, the emission of radiation from atoms is a natural stochastic process.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] It can be simulated directly, or its average behavior can be described by stochastic equations that can themselves be solved using Monte Carlo methods.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] "Indeed, the same computer code can be viewed simultaneously as a 'natural simulation' or as a solution of the equations by natural sampling." Convergence of the Monte Carlo simulation can be checked with the Gelman-Rubin statistic.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] The main idea behind this method is that the results are computed based on repeated random sampling and statistical analysis.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] The Monte Carlo simulation is, in fact, random experimentations, in the case that, the results of these experiments are not well known.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo simulations are typically characterized by many unknown parameters, many of which are difficult to obtain experimentally.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo simulation methods do not always require truly random numbers to be useful (although, for some applications such as primality testing, unpredictability is vital).
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Many of the most useful techniques use deterministic, pseudorandom sequences, making it easy to test and re-run simulations.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] The only quality usually necessary to make good simulations is for the pseudo-random sequence to appear "random enough" in a certain sense.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] What this means depends on the application, but typically they should pass a series of statistical tests.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Testing that the numbers are uniformly distributed or follow another desired distribution when a large enough number of elements of the sequence are considered is one of the simplest and most common ones.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Weak correlations between successive samples are also often desirable/necessary.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Pseudo-random number sampling algorithms are used to transform uniformly distributed pseudo-random numbers into numbers that are distributed according to a given probability distribution.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Low-discrepancy sequences are often used instead of random sampling from a space as they ensure even coverage and normally have a faster order of convergence than Monte Carlo simulations using random or pseudorandom sequences.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Methods based on their use are called quasi-Monte Carlo methods.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] No statistically significant difference was found between models generated with typical pseudorandom number generators and RDRAND for trials consisting of the generation of 107 random numbers.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] There are ways of using probabilities that are definitely not Monte Carlo simulations – for example, deterministic modeling using single-point estimates.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Each uncertain variable within a model is assigned a "best guess" estimate.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Scenarios (such as best, worst, or most likely case) for each input variable are chosen and the results recorded.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] By contrast, Monte Carlo simulations sample from a probability distribution for each variable to produce hundreds or thousands of possible outcomes.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] The results are analyzed to get probabilities of different outcomes occurring.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] This is because the "what if" analysis gives equal weight to all scenarios (see quantifying uncertainty in corporate finance), while the Monte Carlo method hardly samples in the very low probability regions.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] The samples in such regions are called "rare events".
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are especially useful for simulating phenomena with significant uncertainty in inputs and systems with many coupled degrees of freedom.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] In statistical physics, Monte Carlo molecular modeling is an alternative to computational molecular dynamics, and Monte Carlo methods are used to compute statistical field theories of simple particle and polymer systems.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Quantum Monte Carlo methods solve the many-body problem for quantum systems.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] In radiation materials science, the binary collision approximation for simulating ion implantation is usually based on a Monte Carlo approach to select the next colliding atom.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] In experimental particle physics, Monte Carlo methods are used for designing detectors, understanding their behavior and comparing experimental data to theory.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] In astrophysics, they are used in such diverse manners as to model both galaxy evolution and microwave radiation transmission through a rough planetary surface.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are also used in the ensemble models that form the basis of modern weather forecasting.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are widely used in engineering for sensitivity analysis and quantitative probabilistic analysis in process design.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] The need arises from the interactive, co-linear and non-linear behavior of typical process simulations.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] The Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change relies on Monte Carlo methods in probability density function analysis of radiative forcing.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are used in various fields of computational biology, for example for Bayesian inference in phylogeny, or for studying biological systems such as genomes, proteins, or membranes.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] The systems can be studied in the coarse-grained or *ab initio* frameworks depending on the desired accuracy.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Computer simulations allow monitoring of the local environment of a particular molecule to see if some chemical reaction is happening for instance.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] In cases where it is not feasible to conduct a physical experiment, thought experiments can be conducted, e.g. breaking bonds, introducing impurities at specific sites, changing the local/global structure, or introducing external fields.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Path tracing, occasionally referred to as Monte Carlo ray tracing, renders a 3D scene by randomly tracing samples of possible light paths.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Repeated sampling of any given pixel will eventually cause the average of the samples to converge on the correct solution of the rendering equation, making it one of the most physically accurate 3D graphics rendering methods in existence.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] The standards for Monte Carlo experiments in statistics were set by Sawilowsky.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] To provide implementations of hypothesis tests that are more efficient than exact tests such as permutation tests (which are often impossible to compute) while being more accurate than critical values for asymptotic distributions.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] To provide a random sample from the posterior distribution in Bayesian inference.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] This sample then approximates and summarizes all the essential features of the posterior.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] To provide efficient random estimates of the Hessian matrix of the negative log-likelihood function that may be averaged to form an estimate of the Fisher information matrix.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are also a compromise between approximate randomization and permutation tests.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] An approximate randomization test is based on a specified subset of all permutations (which entails potentially enormous housekeeping of which permutations have been considered).
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] The Monte Carlo approach is based on a specified number of randomly drawn permutations (exchanging a minor loss in precision if a permutation is drawn twice—or more frequently—for the efficiency of not having to track which permutations have already been selected).
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods have been developed into a technique called Monte-Carlo tree search that is useful for searching for the best move in a game.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Possible moves are organized in a search tree and many random simulations are used to estimate the long-term potential of each move.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] A black box simulator represents the opponent's moves.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Expand the leaf node and choose one of its children.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Play a simulated game starting with that node.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Use the results of that simulated game to update the node and its ancestors.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] The net effect, over the course of many simulated games, is that the value of a node representing a move will go up or down, hopefully corresponding to whether or not that node represents a good move.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo Tree Search has been used successfully to play games such as Go, Tantrix, Battleship, Havannah, and Arimaa.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] The US Coast Guard utilizes Monte Carlo methods within its computer modeling software SAROPS in order to calculate the probable locations of vessels during search and rescue operations.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Each simulation can generate as many as ten thousand data points that are randomly distributed based upon provided variables.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Search patterns are then generated based upon extrapolations of these data in order to optimize the probability of containment (POC) and the probability of detection (POD), which together will equal an overall probability of success (POS).
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Ultimately this serves as a practical application of probability distribution in order to provide the swiftest and most expedient method of rescue, saving both lives and resources.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo simulation is commonly used to evaluate the risk and uncertainty that would affect the outcome of different decision options.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods in finance are often used to evaluate investments in projects at a business unit or corporate level, or other financial valuations.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] They can be used to model project schedules, where simulations aggregate estimates for worst-case, best-case, and most likely durations for each task to determine outcomes for the overall project.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are also used in option pricing, default risk analysis.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Additionally, they can be used to estimate the financial impact of medical interventions.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] A Monte Carlo approach was used for evaluating the potential value of a proposed program to help female petitioners in Wisconsin be successful in their applications for harassment and domestic abuse restraining orders.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] It was proposed to help women succeed in their petitions by providing them with greater advocacy thereby potentially reducing the risk of rape and physical assault.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] However, there were many variables in play that could not be estimated perfectly, including the effectiveness of restraining orders, the success rate of petitioners both with and without advocacy, and many others.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] The study ran trials that varied these variables to come up with an overall estimate of the success level of the proposed program as a whole.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo approach had also been used to simulate the number of book publications based on book genre in Malaysia.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] The Monte Carlo simulation utilized previous published National Book publication data and book's price according to book genre in the local market.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] The Monte Carlo results were used to determine what kind of book genre that Malaysians are fond of and was used to compare book publications between Malaysia and Japan.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Nassim Nicholas Taleb writes about Monte Carlo generators in his 2001 book *Fooled by Randomness* as a real instance of the reverse Turing test: a human can be declared unintelligent if their writing cannot be told apart from a generated one.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] In general, the Monte Carlo methods are used in mathematics to solve various problems by generating suitable random numbers (see also Random number generation) and observing that fraction of the numbers that obeys some property or properties.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] The method is useful for obtaining numerical solutions to problems too complicated to solve analytically.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] The most common application of the Monte Carlo method is Monte Carlo integration.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Deterministic numerical integration algorithms work well in a small number of dimensions, but encounter two problems when the functions have many variables.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] First, the number of function evaluations needed increases rapidly with the number of dimensions.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] For example, if 10 evaluations provide adequate accuracy in one dimension, then 10100 points are needed for 100 dimensions—far too many to be computed.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] This is called the curse of dimensionality.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Second, the boundary of a multidimensional region may be very complicated, so it may not be feasible to reduce the problem to an iterated integral.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] 100 dimensions is by no means unusual, since in many physical problems, a "dimension" is equivalent to a degree of freedom.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods provide a way out of this exponential increase in computation time.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] As long as the function in question is reasonably well-behaved, it can be estimated by randomly selecting points in 100-dimensional space, and taking some kind of average of the function values at these points.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] By the central limit theorem, this method displays $\scriptstyle 1/{\sqrt {N}}$ convergence—i.e., quadrupling the number of sampled points halves the error, regardless of the number of dimensions.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] A refinement of this method, known as importance sampling in statistics, involves sampling the points randomly, but more frequently where the integrand is large.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] To do this precisely one would have to already know the integral, but one can approximate the integral by an integral of a similar function or use adaptive routines such as stratified sampling, recursive stratified sampling, adaptive umbrella sampling or the VEGAS algorithm.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] A similar approach, the quasi-Monte Carlo method, uses low-discrepancy sequences.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] These sequences "fill" the area better and sample the most important points more frequently, so quasi-Monte Carlo methods can often converge on the integral more quickly.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Another class of methods for sampling points in a volume is to simulate random walks over it (Markov chain Monte Carlo).
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Such methods include the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm, Gibbs sampling, Wang and Landau algorithm, and interacting type MCMC methodologies such as the sequential Monte Carlo samplers.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Another powerful and very popular application for random numbers in numerical simulation is in numerical optimization.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] The problem is to minimize (or maximize) functions of some vector that often has many dimensions.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Many problems can be phrased in this way: for example, a computer chess program could be seen as trying to find the set of, say, 10 moves that produces the best evaluation function at the end.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] In the traveling salesman problem the goal is to minimize distance traveled.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] There are also applications to engineering design, such as multidisciplinary design optimization.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] It has been applied with quasi-one-dimensional models to solve particle dynamics problems by efficiently exploring large configuration space.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Reference is a comprehensive review of many issues related to simulation and optimization.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] The traveling salesman problem is what is called a conventional optimization problem.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] That is, all the facts (distances between each destination point) needed to determine the optimal path to follow are known with certainty and the goal is to run through the possible travel choices to come up with the one with the lowest total distance.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] If instead of the goal being to minimize the total distance traveled to visit each desired destination but rather to minimize the total time needed to reach each destination, this goes beyond conventional optimization since travel time is inherently uncertain (traffic jams, time of day, etc.).
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Probabilistic formulation of inverse problems leads to the definition of a probability distribution in the model space.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] This probability distribution combines prior information with new information obtained by measuring some observable parameters (data).
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] As, in the general case, the theory linking data with model parameters is nonlinear, the posterior probability in the model space may not be easy to describe (it may be multimodal, some moments may not be defined, etc.).
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] When analyzing an inverse problem, obtaining a maximum likelihood model is usually not sufficient, as normally information on the resolution power of the data is desired.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] In the general case many parameters are modeled, and an inspection of the marginal probability densities of interest may be impractical, or even useless.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] But it is possible to pseudorandomly generate a large collection of models according to the posterior probability distribution and to analyze and display the models in such a way that information on the relative likelihoods of model properties is conveyed to the spectator.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] This can be accomplished by means of an efficient Monte Carlo method, even in cases where no explicit formula for the *a priori* distribution is available.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] The best-known importance sampling method, the Metropolis algorithm, can be generalized, and this gives a method that allows analysis of (possibly highly nonlinear) inverse problems with complex *a priori* information and data with an arbitrary noise distribution.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] Popular exposition of the Monte Carlo Method was conducted by McCracken.
[src:permutation-tests/monte-carlo-method] The method's general philosophy was discussed by Elishakoff and Grüne-Yanoff and Weirich.
[src:permutation-tests/nonparametric-statistics] The first meaning of *nonparametric* involves techniques that do not rely on data belonging to any particular parametric family of probability distributions.
[src:permutation-tests/nonparametric-statistics] An example is order statistics, which are based on ordinal ranking of observations.
[src:permutation-tests/nonparametric-statistics] The discussion following is taken from *Kendall's Advanced Theory of Statistics*.
[src:permutation-tests/nonparametric-statistics] The second meaning of *nonparametric* involves techniques that do not assume that the *structure* of a model is fixed.
[src:permutation-tests/nonparametric-statistics] Typically, the model grows in size to accommodate the complexity of the data.
[src:permutation-tests/nonparametric-statistics] In these techniques, individual variables *are* typically assumed to belong to parametric distributions, and assumptions about the types of associations among variables are also made.
[src:permutation-tests/nonparametric-statistics] Nonparametric methods are widely used for studying populations that have a ranked order (such as movie reviews receiving one to five "stars").
[src:permutation-tests/nonparametric-statistics] The use of nonparametric methods may be necessary when data have a ranking but no clear numerical interpretation, such as when assessing preferences.
[src:permutation-tests/nonparametric-statistics] In terms of levels of measurement, nonparametric methods result in ordinal data.
[src:permutation-tests/nonparametric-statistics] As nonparametric methods make fewer assumptions, their applicability is much more general than the corresponding parametric methods.
[src:permutation-tests/nonparametric-statistics] In particular, they may be applied in situations where less is known about the application in question.
[src:permutation-tests/nonparametric-statistics] Also, due to the reliance on fewer assumptions, nonparametric methods are more robust.
[src:permutation-tests/nonparametric-statistics] Nonparametric methods are sometimes considered simpler to use and more robust than parametric methods, even when the assumptions of parametric methods are justified.
[src:permutation-tests/nonparametric-statistics] This is due to their more general nature, which may make them less susceptible to misuse and misunderstanding.
[src:permutation-tests/nonparametric-statistics] Nonparametric methods can be considered a conservative choice, as they will work even when their assumptions are not met, whereas parametric methods can produce misleading results when their assumptions are violated.
[src:permutation-tests/nonparametric-statistics] The wider applicability and increased robustness of nonparametric tests comes at a cost: in cases where a parametric test's assumptions are met, nonparametric tests have less statistical power.
[src:permutation-tests/nonparametric-statistics] In other words, a larger sample size can be required to draw conclusions with the same degree of confidence.
[src:permutation-tests/nonparametric-statistics] In mathematical statistics, nonparametric models are considered models that do not rely on a parametric assumption of the unknown data distribution (in density estimation problems) or of the regression function (in regression problems).
[src:permutation-tests/nonparametric-statistics] While the goal of any parametric model is the estimation of a finite number of parameters $\theta _{1},\dots ,\theta _{p}\in \mathbb {R}$ , nonparametric models aim to directly estimate the data distribution/regression function.
[src:permutation-tests/nonparametric-statistics] Relevant questions in this field regard the construction of reasonable estimators, consistency, rates of convergence and their optimality, and adaptive estimation.
[src:permutation-tests/nonparametric-statistics] As in parametric statistics, a desirable property for an estimator ${\hat {f_{n}}}$ is that it converges to the target function f as the sample size n goes to infinity, that is, the approximation error converges to zero.
[src:permutation-tests/nonparametric-statistics] Usually, the approximation is measured in terms of $L^{2}$ -norm distance between ${\hat {f_{n}}}$ and f .
[src:permutation-tests/nonparametric-statistics] If an estimator is consistent for all square-integrable f , then it is called **universally consistent**.
[src:permutation-tests/nonparametric-statistics] Many common nonparametric estimators are weakly universally consistent, for example, the Nadarya-Watson estimator, kNNs and certain local polynomial estimators.
[src:permutation-tests/nonparametric-statistics] A central topic in the statistical analysis of nonparametric estimators is their speed of convergence towards the true target function f and whether the speed is optimal, i.e., the convergence is as fast as possible.
[src:permutation-tests/nonparametric-statistics] The most common way to measure the speed of convergence of an estimator is the minimax convergence rate, which considers the expected loss of the estimator in the worst case scenario.
[src:permutation-tests/nonparametric-statistics] Under certain assumptions on the smoothness of f , one can show that there is a minimal convergence rates that no estimator can undercut, and so any estimator achieving this minimal rate is called optimal.
[src:permutation-tests/nonparametric-statistics] The detailed analysis of nonparametric estimators then separates into the estimation of probability densities and regressions functions.
[src:permutation-tests/nonparametric-statistics] Minimax lower bounds are known for different pairs of function classes ${\mathcal {F}}$ and comparison metrics L .
[src:permutation-tests/nonparametric-statistics] In fact, the Hölder spaces and the Sobolev spaces are special cases of some Besov spaces, namely $C^{\alpha }({\mathcal {X}})=B_{\infty ,\infty }^{\alpha }({\mathcal {X}})$ for $\alpha \notin \mathbb {Z}$ and $H^{s}({\mathcal {X}})=B_{2,2}^{s}({\mathcal {X}})$ .
[src:permutation-tests/nonparametric-statistics] Thus, it often suffices to derive lower bounds under Besov-smoothness assumptions.
[src:permutation-tests/nonparametric-statistics] By Scheffé's theorem, the total variation distance $\mathrm {TV} (\mathbb {P} _{f},\mathbb {P} _{g})$ is equivalent to the $L^{1}$ -distance of f and g .
[src:permutation-tests/nonparametric-statistics] The nonparametric rate is thus slower than the parametric rate $n^{-1}$ , especially in large dimensions, and approaches the parametric rate as the smoothness of the density tends to infinity.
[src:permutation-tests/nonparametric-statistics] Kernel density estimators, for instance, achieve the lower bound w.r.t. the MISE under a Sobolev hypothesis class under an appropriate bandwidth choice and is thus minimax optimal.
[src:permutation-tests/nonparametric-statistics] More recently, also score-based generative models have been shown to achieve minimax convergence rates in total variation and in Wasserstein-1 distance for $B_{p,q}^{s}([0,1]^{d})$ -smooth distributions, $s>(1/p-1/2)_{+}$ , that are bounded away from zero from below.
[src:permutation-tests/nonparametric-statistics] Typically, the independent variables $X_{i}$ are assumed to have values in the unit cube $[0,1]^{d}$ and to be either determinsitic points on a grid (deterministic design) or uniformly distributed (random design).
[src:permutation-tests/nonparametric-statistics] The above setting applies to binary classification as well.
[src:permutation-tests/nonparametric-statistics] Indeed, many classification methods are of that form, for example logistic regression, linear discriminant analysis, quadratic discriminant analysis, and k-nearest-neighbors, and support vector machines.
[src:permutation-tests/nonparametric-statistics] Under certain technical assumptions, the following lower bounds are known.
[src:permutation-tests/nonparametric-statistics] Instead, one is interested in methods that achieve the minimax optimal convergence rates not only for one specific smoothness parameter, but across different values.
[src:permutation-tests/nonparametric-statistics] Adaptive estimators are often realized by taking estimators that are minimax optimal for a family of hypothesis classes and by estimating the hyperparameters via a higher-level procedure, such as unbiased risk estimation or cross-validation.
[src:permutation-tests/nonparametric-statistics] Early nonparametric statistics include the median (13th century or earlier, use in estimation by Edward Wright, 1599; see Median § History) and the sign test by John Arbuthnot (1710) in analyzing the human sex ratio at birth (see Sign test § History).
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] A **permutation test** (also called re-randomization test or shuffle test) is an exact statistical hypothesis test.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] A permutation test involves two or more samples.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] The (possibly counterfactual) null hypothesis is that all samples come from the same distribution $H_{0}:F=G$ .
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] Under the null hypothesis, the distribution of the test statistic is obtained by calculating all possible values of the test statistic under possible rearrangements of the observed data.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] Permutation tests are, therefore, a form of resampling.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] Permutation tests can be understood as surrogate data testing where the surrogate data under the null hypothesis are obtained through permutations of the original data.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] In other words, the method by which treatments are allocated to subjects in an experimental design is mirrored in the analysis of that design.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] If the labels are exchangeable under the null hypothesis, then the resulting tests yield exact significance levels; see also exchangeability.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] Confidence intervals can then be derived from the tests.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] The theory has evolved from the works of Ronald Fisher and E.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] Permutation tests should not be confused with randomized tests.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] To illustrate the basic idea of a permutation test, suppose we collect random variables $X_{A}$ and $X_{B}$ for each individual from two groups A and B whose sample means are ${\bar {x}}_{A}$ and ${\bar {x}}_{B}$ , and that we want to know whether $X_{A}$ and $X_{B}$ come from the same distribution.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] Let $n_{A}$ and $n_{B}$ be the sample size collected from each group.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] The permutation test is designed to determine whether the observed difference between the sample means is large enough to reject, at some significance level, the null hypothesis H $_{0}$ that the data drawn from A is from the same distribution as the data drawn from B .
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] First, the difference in means between the two samples is calculated: this is the observed value of the test statistic, $T_{\text{obs}}$ .
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] Next, the observations of groups A and B are pooled, and the difference in sample means is calculated and recorded for every possible way of dividing the pooled values into two groups of size $n_{A}$ and $n_{B}$ (i.e., for every permutation of the group labels A and B).
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] The set of these calculated differences is the exact distribution of possible differences (for this sample) under the null hypothesis that group labels are exchangeable (i.e., are randomly assigned).
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] The one-sided p-value of the test is calculated as the proportion of sampled permutations where the difference in means was greater than $T_{\text{obs}}$ .
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] The two-sided p-value of the test is calculated as the proportion of sampled permutations where the absolute difference was greater than $|T_{\text{obs}}|$ .
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] Many implementations of permutation tests require that the observed data itself be counted as one of the permutations so that the permutation p-value will never be zero.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] Alternatively, if the only purpose of the test is to reject or not reject the null hypothesis, one could sort the recorded differences, and then observe if $T_{\text{obs}}$ is contained within the middle $(1-\alpha )\times 100$ % of them, for some significance level $\alpha$ .
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] If it is not, we reject the hypothesis of identical probability curves at the $\alpha \times 100\%$ significance level.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] To exploit variance reduction with paired samples, a paired permutation test must be applied, see paired difference test.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] This is equivalent to performing a normal, unpaired permutation test, but restricting the set of valid permutations to only those which respect the paired nature of the data by forbidding both halves of any pair from being included in the same partition.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] In the specific but common case where the test statistic is the mean, this is also equivalent to computing a single set of differences of each pair and iterating over all of the $2^{n}$ sign-reversals instead of the usual partitioning approach.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] Permutation tests are a subset of non-parametric statistics.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] Assuming that our experimental data come from data measured from two treatment groups, the method simply generates the distribution of mean differences under the assumption that the two groups are not distinct in terms of the measured variable.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] From this, one then uses the observed statistic ( $T_{\text{obs}}$ above) to see to what extent this statistic is special, i.e., the likelihood of observing the magnitude of such a value (or larger) if the treatment labels had simply been randomized after treatment.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] In contrast to permutation tests, the distributions underlying many popular "classical" statistical tests, such as the *t*-test, *F*-test, *z*-test, and *χ*2 test, are obtained from theoretical probability distributions.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] Fisher's exact test is an example of a commonly used parametric test for evaluating the association between two dichotomous variables.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] When sample sizes are very large, the Pearson's chi-square test will give accurate results.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] For small samples, the chi-square reference distribution cannot be assumed to give a correct description of the probability distribution of the test statistic, and in this situation the use of Fisher's exact test becomes more appropriate.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] Permutation tests exist in many situations where parametric tests do not (e.g., when deriving an optimal test when losses are proportional to the size of an error rather than its square).
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] For example, it is possible in this manner to construct a permutation *t*-test, a permutation ${\textstyle \chi ^{2}}$ test of association, a permutation version of Aly's test for comparing variances and so on.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] Permutation tests exist for any test statistic, regardless of whether or not its distribution is known.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] Thus one is always free to choose the statistic which best discriminates between hypothesis and alternative and which minimizes losses.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] Permutation tests can be used for analyzing unbalanced designs and for combining dependent tests on mixtures of categorical, ordinal, and metric data (Pesarin, 2001) .
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] They can also be used to analyze qualitative data that has been quantitized (i.e., turned into numbers).
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] Permutation tests may be ideal for analyzing quantitized data that do not satisfy statistical assumptions underlying traditional parametric tests (e.g., t-tests, ANOVA), see PERMANOVA.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] Before the 1980s, the burden of creating the reference distribution was overwhelming except for data sets with small sample sizes.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] Since the 1980s, the confluence of relatively inexpensive fast computers and the development of new sophisticated path algorithms applicable in special situations made the application of permutation test methods practical for a wide range of problems.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] It also initiated the addition of exact-test options in the main statistical software packages and the appearance of specialized software for performing a wide range of uni- and multi-variable exact tests and computing test-based "exact" confidence intervals.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] An important assumption behind a permutation test is that the observations are exchangeable under the null hypothesis.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] An important consequence of this assumption is that tests of difference in location (like a permutation t-test) require equal variance under the normality assumption.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] In this respect, the classic permutation t-test shares the same weakness as the classical Student's t-test (the Behrens–Fisher problem).
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] This can be addressed in the same way the classic t-test has been extended to handle unequal variances: by employing the Welch statistic with Satterthwaite adjustment to the degrees of freedom.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] A third alternative in this situation is to use a bootstrap-based test.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] Statistician Phillip Good explains the difference between permutation tests and bootstrap tests the following way: "Permutations test hypotheses concerning distributions; bootstraps test hypotheses concerning parameters.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] As a result, the bootstrap entails less-stringent assumptions." Bootstrap tests are not exact.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] In some cases, a permutation test based on a properly studentized statistic can be asymptotically exact even when the exchangeability assumption is violated.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] Bootstrap-based tests can test with the null hypothesis $H_{0}:F\neq G$ and, therefore, are suited for performing equivalence testing.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] An asymptotically equivalent permutation test can be created when there are too many possible orderings of the data to allow complete enumeration in a convenient manner.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] This is done by generating the reference distribution by Monte Carlo sampling, which takes a small (relative to the total number of permutations) random sample of the possible replicates.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] The realization that this could be applied to any permutation test on any dataset was an important breakthrough in the area of applied statistics.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] The earliest known references to this approach are Eden and Yates (1933) and Dwass (1957).
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] This type of permutation test is known under various names: *approximate permutation test*, *Monte Carlo permutation tests* or *random permutation tests*.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] After N random permutations, it is possible to obtain a confidence interval for the p-value based on the Binomial distribution, see Binomial proportion confidence interval.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] On the other hand, the purpose of estimating the p-value is most often to decide whether $p\leq \alpha$ , where $\scriptstyle \ \alpha$ is the threshold at which the null hypothesis will be rejected (typically $\alpha =0.05$ ).
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] In the example above, the confidence interval only tells us that there is roughly a 50% chance that the p-value is smaller than 0.05, i.e. it is completely unclear whether the null hypothesis should be rejected at a level $\alpha =0.05$ .
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] If it is only important to know whether $p\leq \alpha$ for a given $\alpha$ , it is logical to continue simulating until the statement $p\leq \alpha$ can be established to be true or false with a very low probability of error.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] ( $\epsilon$ will typically be chosen to be extremely small, e.g.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] 1/1000.) Stopping rules to achieve this have been developed which can be incorporated with minimal additional computational cost.
[src:permutation-tests/permutation-test] In fact, depending on the true underlying p-value it will often be found that the number of simulations required is remarkably small (e.g. as low as 5 and often not larger than 100) before a decision can be reached with virtual certainty.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] In statistics, **resampling** is the creation of new samples based on one observed sample.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] Permutation tests rely on resampling the original data assuming the null hypothesis.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] Based on the resampled data it can be concluded how likely the original data is to occur under the null hypothesis.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] It has been called the **plug-in principle**, as it is the method of estimation of functionals of a population distribution by evaluating the same functionals at the empirical distribution based on a sample.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] For example, when estimating the population mean, this method uses the sample mean; to estimate the population median, it uses the sample median; to estimate the population regression line, it uses the sample regression line.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] It may also be used for constructing hypothesis tests.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] It is often used as a robust alternative to inference based on parametric assumptions when those assumptions are in doubt, or where parametric inference is impossible or requires very complicated formulas for the calculation of standard errors.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] Bootstrapping techniques are also used in the updating-selection transitions of particle filters, genetic type algorithms and related resample/reconfiguration Monte Carlo methods used in computational physics.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] In this context, the bootstrap is used to replace sequentially empirical weighted probability measures by empirical measures.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] The bootstrap allows to replace the samples with low weights by copies of the samples with high weights.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] Cross-validation is a statistical method for validating a predictive model.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] Subsets of the data are held out for use as validating sets; a model is fit to the remaining data (a training set) and used to predict for the validation set.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] Averaging the quality of the predictions across the validation sets yields an overall measure of prediction accuracy.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] Cross-validation is employed repeatedly in building decision trees.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] One form of cross-validation leaves out a single observation at a time; this is similar to the jackknife.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] Another, *K*-fold cross-validation, splits the data into *K* subsets; each is held out in turn as the validation set.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] For comparison, in regression analysis methods such as linear regression, each *y* value draws the regression line toward itself, making the prediction of that value appear more accurate than it really is.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] Cross-validation applied to linear regression predicts the *y* value for each observation without using that observation.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] This is often used for deciding how many predictor variables to use in regression.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] Without cross-validation, adding predictors always reduces the residual sum of squares (or possibly leaves it unchanged).
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] In contrast, the cross-validated mean-square error will tend to decrease if valuable predictors are added, but increase if worthless predictors are added.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] Subsampling is an alternative method for approximating the sampling distribution of an estimator.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] 2. resampling is done without replacement.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] The advantage of subsampling is that it is valid under much weaker conditions compared to the bootstrap.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] In particular, a set of sufficient conditions is that the rate of convergence of the estimator is known and that the limiting distribution is continuous.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] In addition, the resample (or subsample) size must tend to infinity together with the sample size but at a smaller rate, so that their ratio converges to zero.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] While subsampling was originally proposed for the case of independent and identically distributed (iid) data only, the methodology has been extended to cover time series data as well; in this case, one resamples blocks of subsequent data rather than individual data points.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] There are many cases of applied interest where subsampling leads to valid inference whereas bootstrapping does not; for example, such cases include examples where the rate of convergence of the estimator is not the square root of the sample size or when the limiting distribution is non-normal.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] When both subsampling and the bootstrap are consistent, the bootstrap is typically more accurate.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] RANSAC is a popular algorithm using subsampling.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] Jackknifing (jackknife cross-validation), is used in statistical inference to estimate the bias and standard error (variance) of a statistic, when a random sample of observations is used to calculate it.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] Historically, this method preceded the invention of the bootstrap with Quenouille inventing this method in 1949 and Tukey extending it in 1958.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] This method was foreshadowed by Mahalanobis who in 1946 suggested repeated estimates of the statistic of interest with half the sample chosen at random.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] He coined the name 'interpenetrating samples' for this method.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] Quenouille invented this method with the intention of reducing the bias of the sample estimate.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] The basic idea behind the jackknife variance estimator lies in systematically recomputing the statistic estimate, leaving out one or more observations at a time from the sample set.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] From this new set of replicates of the statistic, an estimate for the bias and an estimate for the variance of the statistic can be calculated.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] Jackknife is equivalent to the random (subsampling) leave-one-out cross-validation, it only differs in the goal.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] For many statistical parameters the jackknife estimate of variance tends asymptotically to the true value almost surely.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] In technical terms one says that the jackknife estimate is consistent.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] The jackknife is consistent for the sample means, sample variances, central and non-central t-statistics (with possibly non-normal populations), sample coefficient of variation, maximum likelihood estimators, least squares estimators, correlation coefficients and regression coefficients.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] It is not consistent for the sample median.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] In the case of a unimodal variate the ratio of the jackknife variance to the sample variance tends to be distributed as one half the square of a chi square distribution with two degrees of freedom.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] Instead of using the jackknife to estimate the variance, it may instead be applied to the log of the variance.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] This transformation may result in better estimates particularly when the distribution of the variance itself may be non normal.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] The jackknife, like the original bootstrap, is dependent on the independence of the data.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] Extensions of the jackknife to allow for dependence in the data have been proposed.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] One such extension is the delete-a-group method used in association with Poisson sampling.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] Both methods, the bootstrap and the jackknife, estimate the variability of a statistic from the variability of that statistic between subsamples, rather than from parametric assumptions.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] For the more general jackknife, the delete-m observations jackknife, the bootstrap can be seen as a random approximation of it.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] Both yield similar numerical results, which is why each can be seen as approximation to the other.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] Although there are huge theoretical differences in their mathematical insights, the main practical difference for statistics users is that the bootstrap gives different results when repeated on the same data, whereas the jackknife gives exactly the same result each time.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] Because of this, the jackknife is popular when the estimates need to be verified several times before publishing (e.g., official statistics agencies).
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] On the other hand, when this verification feature is not crucial and it is of interest not to have a number but just an idea of its distribution, the bootstrap is preferred (e.g., studies in physics, economics, biological sciences).
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] Whether to use the bootstrap or the jackknife may depend more on operational aspects than on statistical concerns of a survey.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] The jackknife, originally used for bias reduction, is more of a specialized method and only estimates the variance of the point estimator.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] This can be enough for basic statistical inference (e.g., hypothesis testing, confidence intervals).
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] The bootstrap, on the other hand, first estimates the whole distribution (of the point estimator) and then computes the variance from that.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] While powerful and easy, this can become highly computationally intensive.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] "The bootstrap can be applied to both variance and distribution estimation problems.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] However, the bootstrap variance estimator is not as good as the jackknife or the balanced repeated replication (BRR) variance estimator in terms of the empirical results.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] Furthermore, the bootstrap variance estimator usually requires more computations than the jackknife or the BRR.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] There is a special consideration with the jackknife, particularly with the delete-1 observation jackknife.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] It should only be used with smooth, differentiable statistics (e.g., totals, means, proportions, ratios, odd ratios, regression coefficients, etc.; not with medians or quantiles).
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] This could become a practical disadvantage.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] This disadvantage is usually the argument favoring bootstrapping over jackknifing.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] More general jackknifes than the delete-1, such as the delete-m jackknife or the delete-all-but-2 Hodges–Lehmann estimator, overcome this problem for the medians and quantiles by relaxing the smoothness requirements for consistent variance estimation.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] Usually the jackknife is easier to apply to complex sampling schemes than the bootstrap.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] Complex sampling schemes may involve stratification, multiple stages (clustering), varying sampling weights (non-response adjustments, calibration, post-stratification) and under unequal-probability sampling designs.
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] Theoretical aspects of both the bootstrap and the jackknife can be found in Shao and Tu (1995), whereas a basic introduction is accounted in Wolter (2007).
[src:permutation-tests/randomization-test] The bootstrap estimate of model prediction bias is more precise than jackknife estimates with linear models such as linear discriminant function or multiple regression.
